The article described the Pink Tide as authoritarian leaning, when authoritarianism was by no means an exclusive or defining trait of the leftist wave. Countries such as Brazil became significantly less authoritarian by most metrics, previously having been ruled by far-right leadership. Honduras and Bolivia experienced something similar — both being countries previously defined by mass inequality and authoritarian rule. While Honduras reverted as it moved Right, Bolivia remained Left.
